// KNOWN FAILURE (found incidentally while testing ch04 §4.2's new class
// move rules): ch05 §5.1 says a moved-out value must not be used, full
// stop -- this is correctly enforced for a *direct field read* of a
// moved-out object (class_move_construction_use_after_move_is_rejected.scpp),
// but calling a method on a moved-out class object -- even a `const`,
// read-only getter, as here -- is NOT rejected at all: `a.get()` below
// compiles and runs, silently returning a value read back out of `a`'s
// already-moved-from storage (empirically 0, not the original 5),
// instead of being flagged the same way direct field access already
// is. Confirmed to also affect a move *assignment* source and a
// mutating method call, not just move-construction and `const` methods.
class Counter {
private:
    int value;
public:
    Counter(int start) {
        this->value = start;
        return;
    }
    ~Counter() {
        return;
    }
    int get() const {
        return this->value;
    }
};

int main() {
    Counter a(5);
    Counter b(std::move(a));
    return a.get();
}
